 as “the French exception,” the unusually conflictual French political process inherited from the revolutionary past in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries and its accompanying avant-gardism in artistic, literary, and philosophical practice, both of which distinguish France from other European countries. Second, the contributors assess the exhaustion of this tradition in recent years—noted prominently on the occasion of the celebration of the bicentennial of the Revolution in 1989—in a progressive “normalization” of French society that has been the final outcome of the liquidation of the colonial empire, the collapse of Marxism as a social force, and the integration of France into the European Union. The contributors are Jean-Marie Apostolidès, Marc Augé, Barbara Cassin, Françoise Gaillard, Maurice Godelier, Jean-Joseph Goux, Françoise Lionnet, Jean-François Lyotard, Mark Poster, Pierre Saint-Amand, Susan Suleiman, and Philip R. Wood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aApostolides, Jean-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugé, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassin, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaillard, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodelier, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoux, Jean-Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoux, Jean-Joseph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLionnet, Françoise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyotard, Jean-François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoster, Mark, econtributor.4c